#Multiple Regression

Now, we have multiple variables that we believe might influence \(Y\). \[Y_i=\beta_0+\beta_1x_{1i}+....+\beta_2x_{2i}+\epsilon_i\] where \(\epsilon_i\sim{}N(0,\sigma^2)\)

why use multiple regression?

  • it builds better models

  • associations between multiple variables are accounted for

  • it lets us look at interactions between variables

link between storks and babies

data on birth rate and number of storks in 17 countries

# Birth rate, thousands per year
birth<-c(83,87,118,117,59,774,901,106,188,124,551,610,120,367,439,82,1576)
## number stork pairs
storks<-c(100,300,1,5000,9,140,3300,2500,4,5000,5,30000,1500,5000,8000,150,25000)
stork.data<-data.frame(birth=birth,storks=storks)
library(knitr)
kable(stork.data, caption = 'Study of Storks and Babies',align='l')

plot(storks,birth,ylab='Birth Rate', xlab = 'Number Stork Pairs')

Lets fit this simple with a simple linear model

plot(storks,birth,ylab='Birth Rate', xlab = 'Number Stork Pairs')
title('Storks and Birth Rate')
model.simple<-lm(birth~storks)
abline(model.simple)

summary(model.simple)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = birth ~ storks)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -478.8 -166.3 -144.9   -2.0  631.1 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)   
## (Intercept) 2.250e+02  9.356e+01   2.405   0.0295 * 
## storks      2.879e-02  9.402e-03   3.063   0.0079 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 332.2 on 15 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3847, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3437 
## F-statistic:  9.38 on 1 and 15 DF,  p-value: 0.007898

the \(r^2\) is low, but with the low p-value this result is significant. 38% of variance in birth rate is explained by the number of storks.

But what if theres a third variable, one that influences both birth rate and storks? We also have area and population.

## consider two additional factors in the analysis
## area km^2
area<-c(28750,83860,30520,111000,43100,544000,357000,132000,41900,93000,301280,312680,92390,237500,504750,41290,779450)
## human population (10^6)millions
pop<-c(3.2,7.6,9.9,9.0,5.1,56,78,10,15,11,57,38,10,23,39,6.7,56)
stork.data<-data.frame(birth=birth,storks=storks,area=area,pop=pop)
pairs(stork.data)

Storks and birth both seem to have positive correlation to population, maybe thats the relationship between the two? More populations would lead to more births, and create more garbage for storks. Lets make a model to test this

model.multiple<-lm(birth~storks+pop+area)
summary(model.multiple)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = birth ~ storks + pop + area)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -317.24  -52.95    2.44   73.89  295.48 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)  
## (Intercept) -4.824e+01  5.172e+01  -0.933   0.3680  
## storks       8.965e-03  5.024e-03   1.784   0.0977 .
## pop          6.369e+00  2.635e+00   2.417   0.0311 *
## area         9.596e-04  3.240e-04   2.962   0.0110 *
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 140.3 on 13 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9049, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8829 
## F-statistic: 41.23 on 3 and 13 DF,  p-value: 6.644e-07

population and area seem somewhat significant, but storks do not appear to influence birth rate. Were now explaining 90% of the variance, so this model fits much better. Lets look at the confidence intervals

confint(model.multiple)
##                     2.5 %       97.5 %
## (Intercept) -1.599606e+02 63.488907385
## storks      -1.888553e-03  0.019818794
## pop          6.754299e-01 12.062269928
## area         2.596203e-04  0.001659615

the confidence interval for storks includes 0, so we have no evidence that storks effect birth rate. We can remove this from the model. Now we would have the following model for our data: \[Birth = \beta_0+\beta_1pop+\beta_2area+\epsilon_i\]

What if the variables have some interaction with each other? Then, our model might be better represented with the model: \[Birth = \beta_0+\beta_1pop+\beta_2area+\beta_3(pop*area)+\epsilon_i\] Lets test both of these models and compare them

model.multiple2<-lm(birth~pop+area)

model.multiple.int <- lm(birth~pop * area)
anova(model.multiple2,model.multiple.int)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: birth ~ pop + area

## F-statistic: 57.29 on 3 and 13 DF,  p-value: 9.438e-08

Here, it appears that this non-linear term does improve the model, and \(r^2\) is significantly higher.

What are the c$ values?

coef(model.multiple.int)
##   (Intercept)           pop          area      pop:area 
##  1.184274e+02 -1.506284e+00 -1.677709e-04  3.425766e-05

we can graph this as well

## Set range and domain of plot
x  <- seq(min(pop),
          max(pop), 
          length.out = 50);
y  <- seq(min(area), 
          max(area), 
          length.out = 50);

## Interpolate surface
z  <- outer(x,
            y,
            function(x,y){predict(model.multiple.int, data.frame(pop=x, area=y))});
            # This third argument is a function, we're defining it in this call.

p  <- persp(x, 
            y,
            z,
            theta = 30, # used to choose viewing angle
            phi = 30,   # used to choose viewing angle
            col = "lightblue", 
            shade = 0.8, 
            ticktype = "detailed",
            xlab = 'x', 
            ylab = 'y',
            zlab = 'z')
title('Fitted Birth Rate (z), Population (x), Area (y)')
